#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:5
msgid "NumPy 1.23.0 Release Notes"
msgstr "NumPy 1.23.0 發行備註"

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:7
msgid ""
"The NumPy 1.23.0 release continues the ongoing work to improve the handling "
"and promotion of dtypes, increase the execution speed, clarify the "
"documentation, and expire old deprecations. The highlights are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:11
msgid "Implementation of ``loadtxt`` in C, greatly improving its performance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:12
msgid "Exposing DLPack at the Python level for easy data exchange."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:13
msgid "Changes to the promotion and comparisons of structured dtypes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:14
msgid "Improvements to f2py."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:16
msgid "See below for the details,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:20
msgid "New functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:22
msgid ""
"A masked array specialization of ``ndenumerate`` is now available as ``numpy."
"ma.ndenumerate``. It provides an alternative to ``numpy.ndenumerate`` and "
"skips masked values by default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:26
msgid "(`gh-20020 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/20020>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:28
msgid ""
"``numpy.from_dlpack`` has been added to allow easy exchange of data using "
"the DLPack protocol.  It accepts Python objects that implement the "
"``__dlpack__`` and ``__dlpack_device__`` methods and returns a ndarray "
"object which is generally the view of the data of the input object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:33
msgid "(`gh-21145 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/21145>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:37
msgid "Deprecations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:39
msgid ""
"Setting ``__array_finalize__`` to ``None`` is deprecated.  It must now be a "
"method and may wish to call ``super().__array_finalize__(obj)`` after "
"checking for ``None`` or if the NumPy version is sufficiently new."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:43 ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:305
msgid "(`gh-20766 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/20766>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:45
msgid ""
"Using ``axis=32`` (``axis=np.MAXDIMS``) in many cases had the same meaning "
"as ``axis=None``.  This is deprecated and ``axis=None`` must be used instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:49
msgid "(`gh-20920 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/20920>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:51
msgid ""
"The hook function ``PyDataMem_SetEventHook`` has been deprecated and the "
"demonstration of its use in tool/allocation_tracking has been removed.  The "
"ability to track allocations is now built-in to python via ``tracemalloc``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:55
msgid "(`gh-20394 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/20394>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:57
msgid ""
"``numpy.distutils`` has been deprecated, as a result of ``distutils`` itself "
"being deprecated. It will not be present in NumPy for Python >= 3.12, and "
"will be removed completely 2 years after the release of Python 3.12 For more "
"details, see :ref:`distutils-status-migration`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:62
msgid "(`gh-20875 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/20875>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:64
msgid ""
"``numpy.loadtxt`` will now give a ``DeprecationWarning`` when an integer "
"``dtype`` is requested but the value is formatted as a floating point number."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:67
msgid "(`gh-21663 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/21663>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:71
msgid "Expired deprecations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:73
msgid ""
"The ``NpzFile.iteritems()`` and ``NpzFile.iterkeys()`` methods have been "
"removed as part of the continued removal of Python 2 compatibility. This "
"concludes the deprecation from 1.15."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:77
msgid "(`gh-16830 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/16830>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:79
msgid "The ``alen`` and ``asscalar`` functions have been removed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:81
msgid "(`gh-20414 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/20414>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:83
msgid ""
"The ``UPDATEIFCOPY`` array flag has been removed together with the enum "
"``NPY_ARRAY_UPDATEIFCOPY``. The associated (and deprecated) "
"``PyArray_XDECREF_ERR`` was also removed. These were all deprecated in 1.14. "
"They are replaced by ``NPY_ARRAY_WRITEBACKIFCOPY``, that requires calling "
"``PyArray_ResolveWritebackIfCopy`` before the array is deallocated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:89
msgid "(`gh-20589 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/20589>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:91
msgid ""
"Exceptions will be raised during array-like creation.  When an object raised "
"an exception during access of the special attributes ``__array__`` or "
"``__array_interface__``, this exception was usually ignored.  This behaviour "
"was deprecated in 1.21, and the exception will now be raised."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:96
msgid "(`gh-20835 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/20835>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:98
msgid ""
"Multidimensional indexing with non-tuple values is not allowed.  Previously, "
"code such as ``arr[ind]`` where ``ind = [[0, 1], [0, 1]]`` produced a "
"``FutureWarning`` and was interpreted as a multidimensional index (i.e., "
"``arr[tuple(ind)]``). Now this example is treated like an array index over a "
"single dimension (``arr[array(ind)]``).  Multidimensional indexing with "
"anything but a tuple was deprecated in NumPy 1.15."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:105
msgid "(`gh-21029 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/21029>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:107
msgid ""
"Changing to a dtype of different size in F-contiguous arrays is no longer "
"permitted. Deprecated since Numpy 1.11.0. See below for an extended "
"explanation of the effects of this change."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:111 ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:164
msgid "(`gh-20722 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/20722>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:115
msgid "New Features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:118
msgid "crackfortran has support for operator and assignment overloading"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:119
msgid ""
"``crackfortran`` parser now understands operator and assignment definitions "
"in a module. They are added in the ``body`` list of the module which "
"contains a new key ``implementedby`` listing the names of the subroutines or "
"functions implementing the operator or assignment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:125
msgid "(`gh-15006 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15006>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:128
msgid ""
"f2py supports reading access type attributes from derived type statements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:129
msgid ""
"As a result, one does not need to use ``public`` or ``private`` statements "
"to specify derived type access properties."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:132
msgid "(`gh-15844 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15844>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:135
msgid "New parameter ``ndmin`` added to ``genfromtxt``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:136
msgid "This parameter behaves the same as ``ndmin`` from ``numpy.loadtxt``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:138
msgid "(`gh-20500 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/20500>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:141
msgid ""
"``np.loadtxt`` now supports quote character and single converter function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:142
msgid ""
"``numpy.loadtxt`` now supports an additional ``quotechar`` keyword argument "
"which is not set by default.  Using ``quotechar='\"'`` will read quoted "
"fields as used by the Excel CSV dialect."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:146
msgid ""
"Further, it is now possible to pass a single callable rather than a "
"dictionary for the ``converters`` argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:149 ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:293
#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:379
msgid "(`gh-20580 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/20580>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:152
msgid ""
"Changing to dtype of a different size now requires contiguity of only the "
"last axis"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:153
msgid ""
"Previously, viewing an array with a dtype of a different item size required "
"that the entire array be C-contiguous. This limitation would unnecessarily "
"force the user to make contiguous copies of non-contiguous arrays before "
"being able to change the dtype."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:158
msgid ""
"This change affects not only ``ndarray.view``, but other construction "
"mechanisms, including the discouraged direct assignment to ``ndarray.dtype``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:161
msgid ""
"This change expires the deprecation regarding the viewing of F-contiguous "
"arrays, described elsewhere in the release notes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:167
msgid "Deterministic output files for F2PY"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:168
msgid ""
"For F77 inputs, ``f2py`` will generate ``modname-f2pywrappers.f`` "
"unconditionally, though these may be empty.  For free-form inputs, ``modname-"
"f2pywrappers.f``, ``modname-f2pywrappers2.f90`` will both be generated "
"unconditionally, and may be empty. This allows writing generic output rules "
"in ``cmake`` or ``meson`` and other build systems. Older behavior can be "
"restored by passing ``--skip-empty-wrappers`` to ``f2py``. :ref:`f2py-meson` "
"details usage."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:175
msgid "(`gh-21187 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/21187>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:178
msgid "``keepdims`` parameter for ``average``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:179
msgid ""
"The parameter ``keepdims`` was added to the functions ``numpy.average`` and "
"``numpy.ma.average``.  The parameter has the same meaning as it does in "
"reduction functions such as ``numpy.sum`` or ``numpy.mean``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:183
msgid "(`gh-21485 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/21485>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:186
msgid "New parameter ``equal_nan`` added to ``np.unique``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:187
msgid ""
"``np.unique`` was changed in 1.21 to treat all ``NaN`` values as equal and "
"return a single ``NaN``. Setting ``equal_nan=False`` will restore pre-1.21 "
"behavior to treat ``NaNs`` as unique. Defaults to ``True``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:191
msgid "(`gh-21623 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/21623>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:195
msgid "Compatibility notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:198
msgid ""
"1D ``np.linalg.norm`` preserves float input types, even for scalar results"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:199
msgid ""
"Previously, this would promote to ``float64`` when the ``ord`` argument was "
"not one of the explicitly listed values, e.g. ``ord=3``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:202
msgid ""
">>> f32 = np.float32([1, 2])\n"
">>> np.linalg.norm(f32, 2).dtype\n"
"dtype('float32')\n"
">>> np.linalg.norm(f32, 3)\n"
"dtype('float64')  # numpy 1.22\n"
"dtype('float32')  # numpy 1.23"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:209
msgid ""
"This change affects only ``float32`` and ``float16`` vectors with ``ord`` "
"other than ``-Inf``, ``0``, ``1``, ``2``, and ``Inf``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:212
msgid "(`gh-17709 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/17709>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:215
msgid "Changes to structured (void) dtype promotion and comparisons"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:216
msgid ""
"In general, NumPy now defines correct, but slightly limited, promotion for "
"structured dtypes by promoting the subtypes of each field instead of raising "
"an exception::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:220
msgid ""
">>> np.result_type(np.dtype(\"i,i\"), np.dtype(\"i,d\"))\n"
"dtype([('f0', '<i4'), ('f1', '<f8')])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:223
msgid ""
"For promotion matching field names, order, and titles are enforced, however "
"padding is ignored. Promotion involving structured dtypes now always ensures "
"native byte-order for all fields (which may change the result of ``np."
"concatenate``) and ensures that the result will be \"packed\", i.e. all "
"fields are ordered contiguously and padding is removed. See :ref:"
"`structured_dtype_comparison_and_promotion` for further details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:231
msgid ""
"The ``repr`` of aligned structures will now never print the long form "
"including ``offsets`` and ``itemsize`` unless the structure includes padding "
"not guaranteed by ``align=True``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:235
msgid ""
"In alignment with the above changes to the promotion logic, the casting "
"safety has been updated:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:238
msgid ""
"``\"equiv\"`` enforces matching names and titles. The itemsize is allowed to "
"differ due to padding."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:240
msgid "``\"safe\"`` allows mismatching field names and titles"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:241
msgid "The cast safety is limited by the cast safety of each included field."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:243
msgid ""
"The order of fields is used to decide cast safety of each individual field.  "
"Previously, the field names were used and only unsafe casts were possible "
"when names mismatched."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:247
msgid ""
"The main important change here is that name mismatches are now considered "
"\"safe\" casts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:250
msgid "(`gh-19226 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/19226>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:253
msgid "``NPY_RELAXED_STRIDES_CHECKING`` has been removed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:254
msgid ""
"NumPy cannot be compiled with ``NPY_RELAXED_STRIDES_CHECKING=0`` anymore.  "
"Relaxed strides have been the default for many years and the option was "
"initially introduced to allow a smoother transition."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:258
msgid "(`gh-20220 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/20220>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:261
msgid "``np.loadtxt`` has recieved several changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:263
msgid ""
"The row counting of ``numpy.loadtxt`` was fixed.  ``loadtxt`` ignores fully "
"empty lines in the file, but counted them towards ``max_rows``. When "
"``max_rows`` is used and the file contains empty lines, these will now not "
"be counted.  Previously, it was possible that the result contained fewer "
"than ``max_rows`` rows even though more data was available to be read. If "
"the old behaviour is required, ``itertools.islice`` may be used::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:270
msgid ""
"import itertools\n"
"lines = itertools.islice(open(\"file\"), 0, max_rows)\n"
"result = np.loadtxt(lines, ...)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:274
msgid ""
"While generally much faster and improved, ``numpy.loadtxt`` may now fail to "
"converter certain strings to numbers that were previously successfully read. "
"The most important cases for this are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:278
msgid ""
"Parsing floating point values such as ``1.0`` into integers is now "
"deprecated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:279
msgid "Parsing hexadecimal floats such as ``0x3p3`` will fail"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:280
msgid ""
"An ``_`` was previously accepted as a thousands delimiter ``100_000``. This "
"will now result in an error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:283
msgid ""
"If you experience these limitations, they can all be worked around by "
"passing appropriate ``converters=``.  NumPy now supports passing a single "
"converter to be used for all columns to make this more convenient. For "
"example, ``converters=float.fromhex`` can read hexadecimal float numbers and "
"``converters=int`` will be able to read ``100_000``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:289
msgid ""
"Further, the error messages have been generally improved.  However, this "
"means that error types may differ.  In particularly, a ``ValueError`` is now "
"always raised when parsing of a single entry fails."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:297
msgid "Improvements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:300
msgid "``ndarray.__array_finalize__`` is now callable"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:301
msgid ""
"This means subclasses can now use ``super().__array_finalize__(obj)`` "
"without worrying whether ``ndarray`` is their superclass or not. The actual "
"call remains a no-op."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:308
msgid "Add support for VSX4/Power10"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:309
msgid ""
"With VSX4/Power10 enablement, the new instructions available in Power ISA "
"3.1 can be used to accelerate some NumPy operations, e.g., floor_divide, "
"modulo, etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:313
msgid "(`gh-20821 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/20821>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:316
msgid "``np.fromiter`` now accepts objects and subarrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:317
msgid ""
"The ``numpy.fromiter`` function now supports object and subarray dtypes. "
"Please see he function documentation for examples."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:321
msgid "(`gh-20993 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/20993>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:324
msgid "Math C library feature detection now uses correct signatures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:325
msgid ""
"Compiling is preceded by a detection phase to determine whether the "
"underlying libc supports certain math operations. Previously this code did "
"not respect the proper signatures. Fixing this enables compilation for the "
"``wasm-ld`` backend (compilation for web assembly) and reduces the number of "
"warnings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:331
msgid "(`gh-21154 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/21154>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:334
msgid "``np.kron`` now maintains subclass information"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:335
msgid ""
"``np.kron`` maintains subclass information now such as masked arrays while "
"computing the Kronecker product of the inputs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:338
msgid ""
">>> x = ma.array([[1, 2], [3, 4]], mask=[[0, 1], [1, 0]])\n"
">>> np.kron(x,x)\n"
"masked_array(\n"
"  data=[[1, --, --, --],\n"
"        [--, 4, --, --],\n"
"        [--, --, 4, --],\n"
"        [--, --, --, 16]],\n"
"  mask=[[False,  True,  True,  True],\n"
"        [ True, False,  True,  True],\n"
"        [ True,  True, False,  True],\n"
"        [ True,  True,  True, False]],\n"
"  fill_value=999999)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:354
msgid ""
"``np.kron`` output now follows ``ufunc`` ordering (``multiply``) to "
"determine the output class type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:357
msgid ""
">>> class myarr(np.ndarray):\n"
">>>    __array_priority__ = -1\n"
">>> a = np.ones([2, 2])\n"
">>> ma = myarray(a.shape, a.dtype, a.data)\n"
">>> type(np.kron(a, ma)) == np.ndarray\n"
"False # Before it was True\n"
">>> type(np.kron(a, ma)) == myarr\n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:368
msgid "(`gh-21262 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/21262>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:372
msgid "Performance improvements and changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:375
msgid "Faster ``np.loadtxt``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:376
msgid ""
"``numpy.loadtxt`` is now generally much faster than previously as most of it "
"is now implemented in C."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:382
msgid "Faster reduction operators"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:383
msgid ""
"Reduction operations like ``numpy.sum``, ``numpy.prod``, ``numpy.add."
"reduce``, ``numpy.logical_and.reduce`` on contiguous integer-based arrays "
"are now much faster."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:387
msgid "(`gh-21001 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/21001>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:390
msgid "Faster ``np.where``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:391
msgid ""
"``numpy.where`` is now much faster than previously on unpredictable/random "
"input data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:394
msgid "(`gh-21130 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/21130>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:397
msgid "Faster operations on NumPy scalars"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.23.0-notes.rst:398
msgid ""
"Many operations on NumPy scalars are now significantly faster, although rare "
"operations (e.g. with 0-D arrays rather than scalars) may be slower in some "
"cases. However, even with these improvements users who want the best "
"performance for their scalars, may want to convert a known NumPy scalar into "
"a Python one using ``scalar.item()``."
